\frametitle{The Bellman Equation}
    The Bellman equation applies to the state-value function as follows:

    \begin{equation}
        V(s) = \max_a \left( R(s, a) + \gamma \sum_{s'} P(s'|s, a) V(s') \right)
    \end{equation}

    \begin{block}{Meaning}
        The value of a state \( s \) is the maximum expected return among all actions \( a \), considering immediate and discounted future rewards. The parameter \( \gamma \) (discount factor) regulates the value of future benefits (0 â‰¤ \( \gamma \) < 1).
    \end{block}
